Our surprise resulted in the fact that when we returned from the emergency room, he anesthetized my wife as soon as she sat down and was already preparing to do a root canal without prior consent and without saying a word... No budget, no nothing!

When asked to pull out the tooth directly, they flatly refused because that doesn't make any money... Of course they charged us for the consultation even though we were there due to the "doctor's" malpractice.

They had already warned us not to go but we didn't listen, having a freer calendar than the rest (now I understand why...) and not being with the same dentist... We gave them a vote of confidence and left badly off, never again!

Run away as quickly as possible from this dental clinic and this dentist in particular!

I had an appointment for a dental emergency with Dr. Raynaud. I regret not being able to show her and tell me that she is either treating two teeth in my mouth or none when I have an abscess in one tooth and the other has been doing well for months. I explained to Dr Raynaud that I had had a quote of ‚Ç¨610 (‚Ç¨60 for a temporary crown and ‚Ç¨550 for a ceramic crown) and that it was too expensive for me at the moment. So I left with a prescription for antibiotics for my abscess and without a quote for the treatment.
She does not want to treat me and cites an article of law saying that a health professional can refuse care for personal reasons.
If you want to test Dr. Raynaud's intellectual honesty, tell him that you will look elsewhere to compare. A professional with a clear conscience does not fear comparison.
If you are making a crown, you will be asked to sign a quote on which it is written "the patient acknowledges having been given the opportunity to choose their treatment". In addition to ceramic dental crowns at ‚Ç¨550, there are zircon crowns at ‚Ç¨440 and 100% health crowns, with zero remaining charges, which means that it is fully reimbursed by social security and metal mutual insurance. The choice between these three crowns must be given to you.
Dr. Raynaud advised me to go for treatment at the Pasteur hospital or at the mutual dental center, not at another dentist as she should have done. Is this where the poor usually go for treatment according to his vision of things? On the other hand, she didn't advise me to go to the social security dental center, reserved for the indigent? Those who, when they die, are thrown into mass graves, because they cannot afford a coffin? Doctor Raynaud, I reassure you, your ‚Äúflair-√†-fric‚Äù is working well. Indeed, by emptying my bank account, by emptying the bottom of my drawers, the bottom of my pockets and my socks, I have the means to pay for a coffin if I die tomorrow. As for the day after tomorrow, it will depend on the evolution of inflation. I'm also going to start eating only foods that are at the end of their expiration date so I can buy them at a discount.
Dr. Raynaud accused me of saying that dentists pull out teeth to put in implants. In fact, I was thinking more about bridges. How many teeth do you need to have a bridge? Three ?
